      "content": "Early-bird discounts are a powerful tool to create urgency and encourage customers to commit early. The concept is simple: offer a lower price for tickets purchased well in advance of the event. This strategy taps into the **scarcity effect**, where customers feel compelled to act quickly to secure the best deal before it's gone.\n\n**Why it works:**\n- **Psychological urgency**: Customers fear missing out (FOMO) on a good deal.\n- **Cash flow benefits**: Early sales provide upfront revenue to fund event preparations.\n- **Customer commitment**: Early buyers are more likely to attend, reducing no-show rates.\n\n**How to apply it:**\n1. Set a clear deadline for the early-bird period (e.g., \"First 100 tickets\" or \"Until [date]\").\n2. Highlight the discount in all marketing materials (e.g., \"Save 20% if you book by Friday!\").\n3. Use countdown timers on your website to reinforce urgency.\n\n**Example:** A music festival offers tickets at $50 for the first month, then increases the price to $75. The early-bird discount not only drives initial sales but also creates buzz around the event."
